body: Code completion used to avoid forming single expression closures/function bodies when the single expression contained the code completion expression because a contextual type mismatch could result in types not being applied to the AST, giving no completions.<nl><nl>Completions that have been migrated to the new solver-based completion mechanism don't need this behavior, however. Rather than trying to guess whether the type of completion we're going to end up performing is one of the ones that haven't been migrated to the solver yet when parsing, instead just always form single-expression closures/function bodies (like we do for regular compilation) and undo the transformation if and when we know we're going to perform a completion kind we haven't migrated yet.<nl><nl>Once all completion kinds are migrated, the undo-ing code can be removed.
title: [Parse][CodeCompletion] Don't special case code completion when forming single-expression closures/function bodies (NFC)
commit_message: [Parse][CodeCompletion] Don't special case code completion when forming single-expression closures/function bodies (NFC)<nl><nl>Code completion used to avoid forming single expression closures/function<nl>bodies when the single expression contained the code completion expression<nl>because a contextual type mismatch could result in types not being applied<nl>to the AST, giving no completions.<nl><nl>Completions that have been migrated to the new solver-based completion<nl>mechanism don't need this behavior, however. Rather than trying to guess<nl>whether the type of completion we're going to end up performing is one of<nl>the ones that haven't been migrated to the solver yet when parsing, instead<nl>just always form single-expression closures/function bodies (like we do for<nl>regular compilation) and undo the transformation if and when we know we're<nl>going to perform a completion kind we haven't migrated yet.<nl><nl>Once all completion kinds are migrated, the undo-ing code can be removed.

body: ##### Summary<nl>For the uninstall script, the command used to delete de netdata user in linux (userdel -f "${username}") deletes the group as well because of the -f option, so the netdata group deletion step fails.<nl><nl>This pull request adds a conditional to only delete the netdata group if it still exists, otherwise just print a message and mark step as OK.<nl><nl>##### Component Name<nl><nl>Uninstall script.<nl><nl>##### Additional Information<nl>From userdel man page:<nl>```<nl>       -f, --force<nl>           This option forces the removal of the user account, even if the user is still logged in. It also forces userdel to remove the user's home directory and mail spool, even if another user uses the<nl>           same home directory or if the mail spool is not owned by the specified user. If USERGROUPS_ENAB is defined to yes in /etc/login.defs and if a group exists with the same name as the deleted user,<nl>           then this group will be removed, even if it is still the primary group of another user.<nl><nl>           Note: This option is dangerous and may leave your system in an inconsistent state.<nl>```<nl><nl>
title: Fixes netdata group deletion on linux for uninstall script

body: os: assume UTF-8 for hostname<nl><nl>Do not assume Latin-1, but rather UTF-8 for the result of getting the<nl>OS hostname.<nl><nl>While in 99 % of cases these strings are stored in ASCII, the OS does<nl>not enforce an encoding on its own, and apparently the hostname is<nl>sometimes set to non-ASCII data (despite at least some versions of<nl>hostname(1) rejecting such input, making it even harder to write a<nl>test for this which would already require root privileges).<nl><nl>In any case, these are short strings, so assuming UTF-8 comes<nl>with no significant overhead.<nl><nl>Fixes: https://github.com/nodejs/node/issues/27848<nl><nl><nl><!--<nl>Thank you for your pull request. body: A simpler solution for show/hide/toggle based on the HTML5 hidden attribute.<nl><nl>To avoid ambiguity regarding how to write CSS to ensure hidden elements should be hidden, the hidden attribute value is set to hidden instead of empty.<nl><nl>This solution is more in line with best practices regarding how to show/hide elements, as it leaves it up to the author to ensure it's hidden properly via CSS (essentially the same as the class-based recommendation, removing/adding classes to control display). <nl><nl>It will also leave the inline style intact, in case this is needed to overrule jQuery's toggling.<nl><nl>For responsive web sites, this will also provide a better way to control whether or not the element should be shown, as it can be controlled through the hidden attribute selector within the context being styled.<nl><nl>Not to mention: this probably performs better than having to remember the computed styles and resetting these when showing the element.<nl><nl>Another option is to add a method "unhide" that removes the hidden attribute, whereas "show" retains the functionality of the current code where its inline style is changed to force it to show.
title: Hidden attribute solution for show/hide/toggle
commit_message: Hidden attribute solution for show/hide/toggle<nl><nl>A simpler solution for show/hide/toggle based on the HTML5 hidden attribute.<nl><nl>To avoid ambiguity regarding how to write CSS to ensure hidden elements should be hidden, the hidden attribute value is set to hidden instead of empty.<nl><nl>This solution is more in line with best practices regarding how to show/hide elements, as it leaves it up to the author to ensure it's hidden properly via CSS (essentially the same as the class-based recommendation, removing/adding classes to control display). <nl><nl>It will also leave the inline style intact, in case this is needed to overrule jQuery's toggling.<nl><nl>For responsive web sites, this will also provide a better way to control whether or not the element should be shown, as it can be controlled through the hidden attribute selector within the context being styled.<nl><nl>Not to mention: this probably performs better than having to remember the computed styles and resetting these when showing the element.<nl><nl>Another option is to add a method "unhide" that removes the hidden attribute, whereas "show" retains the functionality of the current code where its inline style is changed to force it to show.

body: <!-- Please fill in the following information to help us review your PR more efficiently. --><nl><nl>## Brief Information<nl><nl>This pull request is in the type of:<nl><nl>- [ ] bug fixing<nl>- [x] new feature<nl>- [ ] others<nl><nl><nl><nl>### What does this PR do?<nl><nl>In the previous custom series. We can't do transition across different types of shapes. For example, we can't animate from a sector to a rectangle.<nl><nl>In this PR, we bring the ability to do smooth shape morphing across different shapes. It's heavily based on the new add function in zrender https://github.com/ecomfe/zrender/blob/next/src/tool/morphPath.ts<nl><nl>An example of the transition between `map`, `bar`, `bubble` and `pie`(These are all implemented by custom series.)<nl>![Screen Recording 2020-09-13 at 10 27 04 PM](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/841551/93020799-df552e80-f611-11ea-9d3b-1d28912b3dc5.gif)<nl><nl>The transition between hexagon and circle in hexbin example.<nl><nl>![Screen Recording 2020-09-13 at 10 44 10 PM](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/841551/93020993-f34d6000-f612-11ea-9537-1ec5220cfd03.gif)<nl><nl>The transition between different SVG paths.<nl><nl>![Screen Recording 2020-09-12 at 10 42 27 PM](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/841551/93021219-1f1d1580-f614-11ea-9802-37afadaa1ec6.gif)<nl><nl><nl>## Usage<nl><nl>### Are there any API changes?<nl><nl>We add a boolean property called `morph` in the returned element option in `renderItem`. With it enabled, the shape will be morphed from the previous shape smoothly when the type is changed.<nl><nl>For example:<nl>```js<nl>// Render as rectangle at first time.<nl>renderItem(params, api) {<nl>  return {<nl>     type: 'rect'<nl>     ....<nl>   }<nl>}<nl>// Change to a circle.<nl>renderItem(params, api) {<nl>  return {<nl>     type: 'circle',<nl>     // Enable morphing from the previous rectangle.<nl>     morph: true<nl>     ....<nl>   }<nl>}<nl>```
title: [5.0] [Feature] Bring shape morphing ability in custom series
commit_message: feat(custom): add shapeMorphing option in renderItem returns.;fix(custom): fix other props transition when shape morphing

body: We should avoid overriding name if possible because it is confusing to developers (it confused me at least 😅) and it also can causes bugs in code which deal with modules but aren't using the `Module.instance_method(:name).bind` workaround.<nl><nl>I believe 🤞 we can still achieve the desired "method missing" behaviour by only redefining `inspect`.<nl><nl>Refs https://github.com/rails/rails/pull/39819 cc @p8
title: Don't override module name on AV::Base subclass
commit_message: Don't override module name on AV::Base subclass<nl><nl>We should avoid overriding name if possible because it is confusing to<nl>developers and it also can causes bugs in code which deal with modules<nl>but aren't using the Module.instance_method(:name).bind workaround.<nl><nl>I believe we can achieve the desired "method missing" behaviour by just<nl>redefining inspect.<nl><nl>Refs https://github.com/rails/rails/pull/39819

body: **What this PR does / why we need it**:<nl>If ipv6 is disabled the client-go PortForwarder logs an error:<nl>```<nl>E0406 17:26:06.983609   29625 portforward.go:209] Unable to create listener: Error listen tcp6 [::1]:30143: socket: address family not supported by protocol<nl>```<nl>This pull request removes this error log. Reasons:<nl>* Tunnel creation might still succeed on ipv4 and the error just confuses the user (see https://github.com/kubernetes/helm/issues/2223).<nl>* If the tunnel can't be created the error gets also loggen in `listenOnPort`.<nl>* runtime.HandleError should only be used on errors "_when a non-user facing piece of code cannot return an error"_ which isn't the case here.<nl><nl>**Which issue this PR fixes**<nl>Fixes https://github.com/kubernetes/helm/issues/2223
title: client-go PortForwarder: don't log an error if net.Listen fails
commit_message: client-go PortForwarder: don't log an error if net.Listen fails

body: Improve documentation and naming for derivative function SILGen.<nl><nl>SILGen generates thunks for derivative functions registered via<nl>`@differentiable` and `@differentiating` attributes.<nl><nl>Currently, two SILGen derivative thunk kinds exist:<nl>- `SILGenModule::getOrCreateAutoDiffDerivativeForwardingThunk`<nl>  - This creates a simple thunk that forwards arguments and returns<nl>    results. This is generated when no reabstraction or self reordering<nl>    is necessary.<nl>- `SILGenModule::getOrCreateAutoDiffDerivativeReabstractionThunk`<nl>  - This creates a thunk that performs reabstraction and/or self reordering.

This is generated when no reabstraction or self reordering<nl>    is necessary.<nl>- `SILGenModule::getOrCreateAutoDiffDerivativeReabstractionThunk`<nl>  - This creates a thunk that performs reabstraction and/or self reordering.

body: It's not intended that Storages have 'default' CUDA devices, but this is allowable via the Storage::create_legacy codepath.<nl><nl>This also messages with device_caching, because the initial cache is obtained from the Storage, which may have a 'default' device.<nl><nl>Instead, we materialize a device by allocating 0 bytes via the allocator.<nl>
title: Materialize a non-default device for C2 legacy storage.
commit_message: Materialize a non-default device for C2 legacy storage.<nl><nl>It's not intended that Storages have 'default' CUDA devices, but this is allowable via the Storage::create_legacy codepath.<nl><nl>This also messages with device_caching, because the initial cache is obtained from the Storage, which may have a 'default' device.<nl><nl>Instead, we materialize a device by allocating 0 bytes via the allocator.

body: Also remove requirement for calicoctl from Debian / salt installed nodes and clean it up a little by deploying calico-node with a manifest rather than calicoctl. This also makes it more reliable by retrying properly.How to use:```make quick-releaseNETWORK_POLICY_PROVIDER=calico cluster/kube-up.sh```One place where I was uncertain:- CPU allocations (on the master particularly, where there's very little spare capacity). I took some from etcd, but if there's a better way to decide this, I'm happy to change it.---This change is [](https://reviewable.kubernetes.io/reviews/kubernetes/kubernetes/29037)
title: Add support for kube-up.sh to deploy Calico network policy to GCI masters
commit_message: kube-up: move Calico policy components off master, and add support for GCI master
